Gemini said
It’s a classic "welcome to Arch" moment—having the hardware but needing to manually wire the software. Since you're on a Framework, you have the hardware support, but Hyprland doesn't handle media keys out of the box.

You likely installed brightnessctl or light. For this guide, I’ll assume brightnessctl as it’s the most common and reliable for Framework laptops.

1. Identify your keys
Framework laptops usually use XF86MonBrightnessUp and XF86MonBrightnessDown. You need to map these in your Hyprland configuration.

2. Update your Hyprland Config
Open your config file (usually at ~/.config/hypr/hyprland.conf) and add the following lines.

Note: We use the e flag (repeat) so you can hold the key down, and the l flag so it works even if the screen is locked.

Bash
# Brightness control
bindel = , XF86MonBrightnessUp, exec, brightnessctl set 5%+
bindel = , XF86MonBrightnessDown, exec, brightnessctl set 5%-
3. Permissions (The "Why isn't it working?" fix)
If the commands work with sudo but not by themselves, your user isn't in the video group. Run this command:

Bash
sudo usermod -aG video $USER
You will need to log out and back in for this change to take effect.

Troubleshooting & Refinements
If you don't have brightnessctl: Install it via sudo pacman -S brightnessctl.

Check the device name: Frameworks usually "just work," but you can verify your backlight device by running brightnessctl -l.

Minimum Brightness: To prevent accidentally turning your screen completely black, you can set a floor:
bindel = , XF86MonBrightnessDown, exec, brightnessctl set 5%- && [ $(brightnessctl get) -lt 500 ] && brightnessctl set 500 (adjust numbers based on your max brightness).

Framework Specific Tip
If you are using the Framework 13 (AMD) or Framework 16, ensure your kernel is up to date (6.1+). Older kernels had quirks with how the ambient light sensor interfered with manual brightness steps.

